  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency Shelter and NFI Assistance to Drought-Displaced Communities in Herat and Badghis Provinces</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Afghanistan Humanitarian Fund (AHF) fifth Reserve Allocation was launched after a revision of the Humanitarian Response Plan (HRP), which was revised based on a situational analysis outlining the extent of the drought emergency in the North and West of Afghanistan, and following presentation of an updated humanitarian context to UNOCHA and the Humanitarian Country Team (HCT) in early November 2018. Findings from recent needs assessments indicate the urgent need to provide emergency shelter and Non-Food Items (NFIs) assistance with the majority of the displaced populations living in the open and under makeshift shelters. The Reserve Allocation was therefore released to directly respond to this high priority need.

The proposed project will target drought- displaced communities in Injil District (Herat Province) and Qala-e-Naw District (Badghis Province) for an emergency shelter and household NFI support that meet Cluster specifications. The project, implemented directly by the Norwegian Refugee Council (NRC), continuing recent and long-standing interventions in these areas, is aligned with the CHF Reserve Strategy priorities, and has been coordinated through relevant fora, notably the Afghanistan Emergency Shelter and NFI (ES/NFI) Cluster. 

NRC proposes to provide a combination of emergency shelters in the form of in-kind family tents for 6,350 vulnerable families (32,175 individuals) and unconditional NFI cash support of USD $85 (~6,375 AFN- distribution time market exchange rate to be used) for 2,775 households (13,755 individuals) as markets remain functional in target project locations. This will fill existing gaps in ES/ NFI support to the affected population and complement activities currently being undertaken through other funding mechanisms.

Based on assumed overlaps on provision of assistance in order to avoid double counting, the proposed project will target a total of 7,043 vulnerable households, reaching 35,637 individuals.</narrative>
  </description>
